President Barack Obama has announced his intent to nominate William J. Hybl for the position of Member of the United States Advisory Commission on Public Diplomacy at the Department of State. Hybl is currently the Chairman and CEO of El Pomar Foundation, one of the largest private foundations in the Rocky Mountain west. He has also served as Chairman and Vice Chairman of the International Foundation for Electoral Systems (IFES) and as Chairman and Vice Chairman of the U.S. Advisory Commission on Public Diplomacy under Presidents George H. W. Bush, William J. Clinton, and George W. Bush. Additionally, he was appointed as the U.S. Representative to the 56th General Assembly of the United Nations by President George W. Bush in 2001. Hybl has a background in politics, having served as Special Counsel to President Ronald Reagan in 1981 and as a member of the Colorado House of Representatives in 1972. He is recognized for his outstanding service to America's young people and has received the Outward Bound Compass Award. Furthermore, he is President Emeritus of the United States Olympic Committee and serves as Chairman of the U.S. Olympic Foundation. Hybl holds a J.D. from the University of Colorado and a B.A. in Political Science from Colorado College.